":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Francie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Franceis</i>, modern French <i>François</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>, originally ‘Frank’, though later used to denote a Frenchman. The personal name owed much of its popularity during the Middle Ages to the fame of Saint Francis of Assisi (1181–1226), whose baptismal name was actually <i>Giovanni</i> but who was nicknamed <i>Francisco</i> because his father was absent in France at the time of his birth. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Francesco   and Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian   Franc  , and also their derivatives, e.g. Croatian <b>Francišković</b> (see   Francisco   4).","English: ethnic name from the Old French adjective <i>Franceis</i> ‘French’ (see 1 above).","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames, or an adoption of the non-Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferenc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Casimir, Iwan, Zbigniew.","Hungarian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), Slovenian, and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Ferenc</i>, a Hungarian form of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Fraczek","meanings":["Polish (<b>Frączek</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Franciszek</i>, an equivalent of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ). It is found mainly in Lesser Poland."]},{"name":"Chico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jesus, Pedro, Rafael, Bernardo, Camilo, Cirilo, Juan, Miguel, Ramona, Ruben.","Spanish: from <i>chico</i> ‘small, young’ (of uncertain origin, perhaps from Latin <i>ciccum</i> ‘trifle’), applied as a nickname for a small man, or for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name.","Portuguese: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francisco</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Francesco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Gabriele, Giovanni, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Carlota, Garcia, Romana.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Francesco</i> (from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>), an equivalent of   Francis  ."]},{"name":"Di Cicco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Pasquale, Carlo, Cosmo, Giovanni, Giulio, Giuseppe, Nicola, Attilio, Benedetto, Carmela.","Italian: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Ceccarelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Dino, Angelo, Dante, Quinto, Sesto, Aldo, Americo, Amerigo, Arcangelo, Augusto, Aurelio, Franco, Gino, Guido, Italo, Leoncio, Renato, Roberto, Tino, Tito, Valerio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Ceccarello</i>, a diminutive of <i>Cecco</i>, itself a diminutive <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Di Cioccio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Cosmo, Mario, Cesidio, Dante, Guido, Salvatore, Aldo, Americo, Benito, Biagio, Domenico, Ezio, Flavio, Nunzio, Quintino, Silverio.","Italian: patronymic from a personal name of uncertain derivation,possibly a pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cillo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Americo, Aniello, Antonio, Carmine, Gianna, Giovanni, Guido, Livio, Rocco, Vito.","Italian: from a shortened pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (equivalent of   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cisco","meanings":["Italian (Veneto): from the personal name <i>Cisco</i>, a short form of <i>Francesco</i>, Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","American shortened form of the surname   Francisco   (which is in part of German and presumably also of French origin) and thus a variant of   Sisco   and   Sesco  ."]},{"name":"Fran","meanings":["Croatian: from a short form of local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","Spanish: probably an altered form of Catalan   Franc  .","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): from a short form of the Spanish personal name   Franco   or   Francisco  ."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Francie was born about 0969, in Clermont, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Yves d'ALENCON, was 28 and her mother, Godehilde de Ponthieu, was 31. She had at least 1 son with Baudouin I de Clermont-en-Beauvaisis."},"et":{"about 0969–":"umbes 0969–Surnud","0969–Female":"0969–Surnud","0965–1023":"0965–1023","0990–1042":"0990–1042","0942–1024":"0942–1024","0939–1004":"0939–1004","0942":"0942","about 0969":"umbes 0969","1004":"1004","1024":"1024","0990":"0990","ABT 990":"umbes 0990","1023":"1023","0939":"0939","1042":"1042","0969":"0969","0965":"0965","Clermont-en-Beauvaisis, Clermont, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Clermont, Oise, Hauts-de-France, Prant